~2 lbs. of meat per day supposedly being the magic number to saturate the tissue stores of creatine. It's known one should take creatine supplements together with a sugary drink like grape juice for better absorption and red Burgundy is a dry (sugar-poor) wine, but as Evola said:

Looking at the massive amounts of meat a musketeer would consumer per Alex. Dumas' book ("a larded hare, a fat capon, mutton leg dressed with garlic, and four bottles of old Burgundy"), a musketeer would get as much creatine from his diet as a gymcel supplementing creatine today.

"We find that no man but the most primitive will choose or prefer only those foods best suited for the survival of his organism. This is the case not because he is “corrupt” but because he is man." Thus dry Burgundy goes with the capons.

There is an enigmatic Gene Wolfe short story, I forgot the name, which involves two men dueling with swords and upon clashing the swords together one feels some sort of energy "emanating" from him and wins with the other dying, but is very exhausted afterwards and soon falls ill.

I suspect this "psychic" aspect of sword fighting played a larger role in chivalric duels and such in the past than we are likely to assume as also the warrior caste is the one where the psychic aspect dominates as Guido de Giorgio writes. Psychic energies constitute warriorhood.

This is a certified dark peating method, but if you enjoy having access to sweet orange juice and are able to also get some Italian lemon liquor Limoncello, the two together makes for a good simple cocktail, tastes tangy and adds some zest to the citrus flavor. Good for hot days.

There are lots of complicated cocktails with Limoncello ofc. and if you enjoy more frothy ones I guess you can improvise a variation of the "Orange Julius" one with raw eggs and orange juice with Limocello added, but the simple OJ and lemon liquor zesty taste is very pleasant...

"Leprosy? That's easily curable. But it's true that he should socially isolate before the treatment is successful."

... that you must remain friendly to the one who "carries the ring" and be prepared to provide him aid and comfort him and that you must not repel him or expose him to the enemy. That is the extent of most of us' duty. You are not asked to be the ascetic, but only to shelter him.

If you ever feel despair reading monastic religious literature like St. Ign. Brianchaninov at not even coming close to the standards of fasting, prayer, etc. described there, remember (to borrow an image from Tolkien) that you are not asked to be the ring-bearer yourself, but ...

Basically there is a reason why monastics among themselves do things like read the entire Psalter multiple times daily but their advice to married people in the world is like "try not to get quarrelsome if you're tired from your job". We're not all playing on the same difficulty.
